  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Let <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> be a nilpotent Lie group endowed with a left invariant Riemannian metric, <math altimg="si143.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi></math> its Euclidean Lie algebra and <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> the center of <math altimg="si143.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi></math> . By using an orthonormal basis adapted to the splitting <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>⊕</mo><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>⊕</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>⊥</mo></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>⊕</mo><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo></mrow></msup></math> , where <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> (resp. <math altimg="si109.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo></mrow></msup></math> ) is the orthogonal of <math altimg="si11.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math> in <math altimg="si58.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math> (resp. is the orthogonal of <math altimg="si12.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>⊥</mo></mrow></msup></math> in <math altimg="si10.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>⊥</mo></mrow></msup></math> ), we show that the signature of the Ricci operator of <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>G</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>h</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> is determined by the dimensions of the vector spaces <math altimg="si11.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></math> , <math altimg="si12.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>⊥</mo></mrow></msup></math> and the signature of a symmetric matrix of order <math altimg="si13.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">dim</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">dim</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>∩</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> . This permits to associate to G a subset <math altimg="si14.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">Sign</mi></mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> of <math altimg="si15.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">N</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math> depending only on the Lie algebra structure, easy to compute and such that, for any left invariant Riemannian metric on G , the signature of its Ricci operator belongs to <math altimg="si14.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">Sign</mi></mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> . We show also that for any nilpotent Lie group of dimension less or equal to 6, <math altimg="si14.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><mi mathvariant="bold">Sign</mi></mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="fraktur">g</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> is actually the set of signatures of the Ricci operators of all left invariant Riemannian metrics on G . We give also some general results which support the conjecture that the last result is true in any dimension.</subfield>
